# CSV Parser - Usage Examples

Comprehensive examples demonstrating all features of the CSV Parser library.

## Table of Contents

1. [Basic Usage](#basic-usage)
2. [Quoted Fields](#quoted-fields)
3. [Custom Delimiters](#custom-delimiters)
4. [Type Coercion](#type-coercion)
5. [Error Handling](#error-handling)
6. [Filtering](#filtering)
7. [Aggregation](#aggregation)
8. [Real-World Scenarios](#real-world-scenarios)

---

## Basic Usage

### Simple CSV Parsing

```typescript
import parseCSV from './csv-parser';

const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,New York
Jane,25,Los Angeles
Bob,35,Chicago`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.headers);
// ['name', 'age', 'city']

console.log(result.rows);
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, city: 'New York' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, city: 'Los Angeles' },
//   { name: 'Bob', age: 35, city: 'Chicago' }
// ]

console.log(result.errors);
// []
```

### Accessing Data

```typescript
const person = result.rows[0];
console.log(person.name);    // 'John'
console.log(person.age);     // 30 (number)
console.log(person.city);    // 'New York'

// Iterate over rows
result.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log(`${row.name} is ${row.age} years old`);
});
```

---

## Quoted Fields

### Commas Inside Quoted Fields

```typescript
const csv = `name,address
"Smith, John","123 Main St, New York, NY 10001"
"Johnson, Jane","456 Oak Ave, Los Angeles, CA 90001"`;

